{
  "texts": [
    "Assuming the degree of imperfections added is controlled, the pollster can still learn about the relationships of interest, without breaching users' privacy.",
    "Historically, statistical techniques such as multiple imputation (Raghunathan et al. 2003) have been used to generate partially synthetic datasets, though these have been limited to well-structured data such as those provided by the census tables (i.e., age, ethnicity, education level, etc.).",
    "More recently, advances in generative deep-learning (e.g., Large Language Models (LLMs) (Vaswani et al. 2017) such as GPT-4, Bard, LLaMA, etc.)",
    "have enabled a new level of privacy protection, providing researchers with the ability to simulate synthetic users who share fundamentally important characteristics with the original while being otherwise completely fictional.",
    "Generative models have been used for implementing differential privacy (Acs et al. 2018), including for location data (Bindschaedler and Shokri 2016), image data (Takagi et al. 2021), natural language (Li et al. 2021) as well as in other applications."
  ]
}